<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-345-676  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 345 676.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 12 1989 v23 n24 p76(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Portable LANs cushion the jump down. (technology issues indownsizing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hurwicz, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A number of challenges present themselves when users must changefrom one computing platform to another: new interfaces must belearned and a variety of support operations must be implementedfor the new platform.andP;  Although difficult to manage, there hasbeen no real alternative to downsizing if users want or need toget the benefits of the microcomputer client-server platform.andP;  Nowa new product, a portable local area network (LAN) operatingsystem, can be installed onto a mainframe, allowing the host to beused as a LAN server.andP;  Portable LAN operating systems are designedto work on a number of platforms, allowing any size of computer toact as the host.andP;  Once implemented, a portable operating systemallows a system to be downsized in a functional sense without thetrauma associated with changing the hardware.andP;  The hardware can bedownsized later, once users are more comfortable with the system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Network Operating SystemsNew ProductSoftware MigrationLocal Area Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>